         <ab>
            Hi Jack,
            
            Working hard?
            
            See below.
            
            On 8/4/2017 8:32 AM, Jack Bowers wrote:
            Hi Mille,
            
            Ah yeah I thought so, thanks for clearing it up ;-)
            
            Could you help me with one small thing? Just one sentence from booklet <ref target="file:/Users/jackbowers/Box%20Sync/Language_Data/Mixtec/SIL_docs/L152/L152-tok.xml">L152 "Viko tanta'a lakuku tsi ncho'o"</ref>)
            <lb/>
            There are a bunch of sentences with the modal(?) prefix on the verb "kua'a"
            e.g.
            <lb/>
            "<seg xml:id="d1e38" xml:lang="mix">
               <w xml:id="d1e39">Mee</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e41">nakua'a</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e46">ña</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e48">ko'o</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e53">na</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e55">tsi</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e57">ña</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e60">katsi</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e62">na</w>
            </seg>" ‑ "<spanGrp type="annotations">
               <span target="#d1e38" resp="#MN">I will give them something to drink and food to eat.</span>
               <span target="#d1e38" resp="#MN" xml:lang="es" type="translation">Yo les voy a dar bebida y alimentos.</span>
            </spanGrp>
            <lb/>"Something like that.
            "I can give/bring (ña=to it?) plates for people to eat (on/with?)"  <q resp="#MN"> Didnꞌt we talk about that?  When we  published that  booklet and other booklets, we wrote "na" attached to the verb as a prefix.  I prefer to write it separate from the verb and I am doing it that way, since "<seg xml:id="d1e73" xml:lang="mix">
                  <w xml:id="d1e74">na</w>
               </seg>" is the counterpart of "<seg xml:id="d1e77" xml:lang="mix">
                  <w xml:id="d1e78">ma</w>
               </seg>" which we write separate from the verb.</q>  
            
            &gt; How do you guys characterize the na- prefix (linguistically)?  <q resp="#MN">"<seg xml:id="d1e84" xml:lang="mix">
                  <w xml:id="d1e85">na</w>
               </seg>" has two senses; <spanGrp type="gram">
                  <span type="mood" n="1" target="#" ana="#SUBJ"/>
                  <span type="mood" n="2" target="#" ana="#HORT"/>
               </spanGrp>subjunctive and hortative.  But when we are glossing texts, we gloss "na" as subjunctive, it doesnꞌt matter what its use is in the text.  Then when writing a paper we explain the use of "na" in the text (either subjunctive or hortative).  Some examples:</q>
            <lb/>
            "<seg xml:id="d1e94" xml:lang="mix" type="declarative">
               <w xml:id="d1e95">Chiꞌi</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e97">kue</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e99">chikui</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e101">nu</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e103" orig="ñuꞌú">ñu'ú</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e105">takua</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e107">na</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e109">ntantsia</w>
               <pc>.</pc>
            </seg>"  <lb/>"<spanGrp type="annotations">
               <span target="#d1e94" xml:lang="en" resp="#JB" type="translation">We water the field so that it is moistened.</span>
               <span target="#d1e94" xml:lang="es" resp="#MN" type="translation">Regamos el campo para que se humedezca.</span>
            </spanGrp>"
            <spanGrp type="gram">
               <span type="mood" target="#" ana="#SUBJ">subjunctive</span>
               <!-- tag: prefix, verb phrase, clause or all sentence?-->
            </spanGrp>
            "<seg xml:id="d1e124" xml:lang="mix">
               <w xml:id="d1e125">Na</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e127">koꞌon</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e129">nu</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e131">itu</w>
               <pc>.</pc>
            </seg>" <lb/> "<spanGrp type="annotations">
               <span target="#d1e124" xml:lang="en" type="translation">Let's go to the cornfield.</span>
               <span target="#d1e124" resp="#MN" xml:lang="es" type="translation">Vayamos a la milpa.</span>
            </spanGrp>"
            <spanGrp type="gram">
               <span type="mood" target="#" ana="#">(hortative)</span>
            </spanGrp>
            "<seg xml:id="d1e147" xml:lang="mix">
               <w xml:id="d1e148">Na</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e150">kaꞌan</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e152">ko</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e154" orig="saꞌan">sa'an</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e156">ko</w>
               <pc>.</pc>
            </seg>" <lb/> "<spanGrp type="annotations">
               <span target="#d1e147" xml:lang="en" type="translation">Let's speak our language.</span>
               <span target="#d1e147" xml:lang="es" resp="#MN" type="translation">Hablemos nuestro idioma.</span>
            </spanGrp>" 
            <spanGrp type="gram">
               <span type="mood" target="#" ana="#HORT">(hortative)</span>
            </spanGrp>
            <lb/>
            <q resp="#MN"> When "na" is used in 1st singular like the example above, the speaker has a real intention to do what he/ she said. </q>
            
            &gt; Is the translation of this verb correct "can <q resp="#MN">give</q>/bring"?
            
            &gt; How would you translate the rest of the things going on in that sentence? 
            
            &gt;&gt;Those (ña)'s and (na)'s seem strangely placed to me...<q resp="#MN">Did you have time to read Barbara Hollenbachꞌs paper on "ña"?  (In other Mixtec varieties ja).<lb/>
               Remember that "ña" has different senses, but the main one is like Spanish "lo que".  Here in this sentence is "lo que" but it is translated as "de" in Spanish.  So when you will give food to someone, people you will say, "dar de comer", "dar de beber".   Here "ña" works more or less like a nominalizer. </q>
            <!-- how to tag "nominalizer"?! -->
            <lb/>
            "<seg xml:id="d1e180" sameAs="#d1e38" xml:lang="mix">
               <w xml:id="d1e181">Mee</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e183">nakua'a</w>
               <!-- here's a case to use <m>! -->
               <w xml:id="d1e188">ña</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e190">ko'o</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e192">na</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e194">tsi</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e196">ña</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e198">katsi</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e200">na</w>
               <pc>.</pc>
            </seg>"
            <lb/>
            <spanGrp type="igt" corresp="#d1e180 #d1e38">
               <span target="#d1e181" ana="#1sg">I</span>
               <span target="#d1e183" ana="#">HORT/SUBJ-</span>
               <span target="#d1e183" ana="#">give</span>
               <span target="#d1e188" ana="#">what</span>
               <span target="#d1e190" ana="#">drink</span>
               <span target="#d1e192" ana="#">they</span>
               <span target="#d1e194" ana="#">and</span>
               <span target="#d1e196" ana="#">what</span>
               <span target="#d1e198" ana="#">eat</span>
               <span target="#d1e200" ana="#">they</span>
            </spanGrp>
            <lb/>
            Tatsa'vi ni nchu'a!! <seg xml:id="d1e206" xml:lang="mix" resp="#MN">
               <w xml:id="d1e207">Tatsaꞌvi</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e209">nchuꞌa</w>
               <w xml:id="d1e211">ni</w>
               <pc>.</pc>
            </seg>
            
            Jack
            
            Na Millie
